english:
  title: Postscript to the Poetry Collection of Left Censor-General Noh Gong's Filial Thinking Pavilion
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When the Respectfully Austere Duke entered the office of Prime Minister during the Xuande era, he served barely a year or two before stepping down. In the Zhengting xinyu year, having passed the examinations, he straightaway entered the Jiphyeonjeon and contributed to the compilation of the Governance Essentials, remaining always within the palace walls. The Duke, as former Left Councilor, would come each seasonal festival to offer congratulations, standing beneath the palace gate—a man nine feet tall, with a radiant countenance and prominent brow, his frost-white beard sparse yet refined, his bearing grave and composed. To behold him was like gazing upon Mount Tai or a towering peak; to approach him was like feeling the warmth of a gentle breeze or the blessing of timely rain.

    Indeed, the Duke stood in court with unyielding integrity, his counsel and proposals unmoved by the chatter of lesser minds. Yet in expressing sincerity and expounding principle, he graciously received the views of others—speaking all he knew, proposing what was right, rejecting what was wrong—thereby guiding the ruler's virtue toward perfection and establishing the realm in lasting peace. Thus he clearly measured himself by the standards of the ancient worthy ministers. At that time, all recognized him as a statesman of the age, yet few knew of his profound virtue and extraordinary filial piety. Perhaps his service to the state was manifest to all, while the cultivation he practiced within his household remained unheard? Or perhaps though he exhausted himself in bringing joy to his parents in the courtyard and chamber, people could not name it as filial piety?

    Now the Left Censor-General is truly his grandson, and the Filial Thinking Pavilion was created by the Duke himself as a legacy for his descendants. Who does not wish to build tombs, construct dwellings, expand gardens, and plant trees for future generations? Who does not desire to inherit the ancestral work and preserve it undiminished through centuries? Yet sometimes ancestors sought only the splendor of rank and office, blazing brilliantly for a moment, leaving no accumulated practice of virtue to hand down. Thus within a generation or two, their vaunted positions vanish without trace, like the song of a bird or the shadow of a flower. Their descendants then, relying on inherited power, grow arrogant and dissolute, never considering from whence their wealth arose, regarding their ancestors' legacy as mere rustic frugality.

    But the Duke and his line are different. Though the Duke achieved great renown and high office, he cherished the grace of his parents' nurture as a child cherishes the lap—never forgetting it for a moment. He gave this feeling form in the very structure of this pavilion, where his heart dwells. The Censor-General, taking the Duke's heart as his own heart and the Duke's filial piety as his filial piety, dwells here, sleeps here, gazes upward in reverence—yet finds it insufficient. Thus he solicited verses from the learned scholars, brilliant as polished jade, resonant as bronze and stone, luminous as autumn waters woven into the fabric of clouds.

    The Book of Songs declares: "The filial child never ceases; may blessings flow eternal to your kind." Is this not the very truth?

    Alas, filial piety is the source of all virtues, the virtue of a single heart. When filial devotion reaches its utmost, it can pierce metal and stone, move heaven and earth, ennoble rulers and bestow grace upon the people, transform customs and change society, transmit inheritance to descendants and shelter posterity. That the Noh clan, from grandfather to grandson, maintains excellence and beauty, shining as a great house of our age—this surely springs from the Respectfully Austere Duke's steadfast, sincere accumulation of filial devotion. Long ago, Bu Xie composed one piece to supplement what was lacking in the southern songs, yet in the end it merely offered general reference and empty words. How could it compare to our Noh clan's Filial Thinking and the weight of the Three Bonds and Five Relationships? Soon these verses shall flow forth as the glorious music of a well-ordered age, continuing the strain of the Artemisia Lament to become the very poetry and music of our Eastern realm—of this there can be no doubt.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Respectfully Austere Duke' (恭肅公) refers to Noh Sasin (盧思愼), a renowned statesman of the Joseon Dynasty.
    - The Jiphyeonjeon (集賢殿) was the Hall of Worthies, Joseon's premier research and advisory institution.
    - The 'Filial Thinking Pavilion' (孝思亭) was a memorial structure built to honor filial piety and ancestral memory.
    - The quotation is from the Book of Songs (詩經), expressing the enduring nature of filial virtue.
    - The 'Three Bonds and Five Relationships' (三綱五常) refers to Confucian principles of social hierarchy and moral conduct.
    - '''The Artemisia Lament'' (蓼莪) is a famous poem in the Book of Songs lamenting parents'' sacrifice and expressing filial gratitude.'
